# [src/components/MerchantNamingModal.tsx](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/expensetracker/mobile/src/components/MerchantNamingModal.tsx) - Technical Explanation

This file acts like adding a new contact on your phone. If the app detects a background SMS expense from an unrecognized source (e.g., `"TXN*AMZN99"`), it pops this modal up on the screen, asking the user to give it a human-friendly name (`"Amazon"`) and a default category.

## 1. Props and Data Setup (Lines 1-46)
```tsx
interface MerchantNamingModalProps {
    visible: boolean;
    merchant: UnknownMerchant | null;
    onComplete: () => void;
    onSkip: () => void;
}
//...
    useEffect(() => {
        if (merchant) {
            setName(merchant.suggestedName);
            setSelectedCategory(merchant.categoryId);
        }
    }, [merchant]);
```
*   **Logical Flow**: The [UnknownMerchant](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/expensetracker/mobile/src/services/SmartSmsProcessor.ts#24-31) object contains the raw ugly SMS string and optionally a hint/suggestion from the parser.
    1. When the modal opens, it auto-fills the text box with the `suggestedName` provided by the AI parser so the user has less typing to do.

## 2. Handling the Save (Lines 48-85)
```tsx
    const handleSave = async () => {
        const displayName = name.trim() || merchant.suggestedName;
        const { user, refreshAll } = require('../store/useAppStore').useAppStore.getState();
        // ...
        await saveMerchantName(merchant.rawName, displayName, selectedCategory, user.id);

        if (merchant.transactionId === -1) {
            const { updateAllTransactionsForMerchant } = require('../services/SmartSmsProcessor');
            await updateAllTransactionsForMerchant(merchant.rawName, displayName, selectedCategory);
        } else {
            await updateTransactionMerchant(merchant.transactionId, displayName, selectedCategory);
        }

        await refreshAll();
        DeviceEventEmitter.emit('TRANSACTION_UPDATED');
        // ...
    };
```
*   **Syntax**: `require(...).getState()` is a trick to read the global Zustand state from *outside* a standard React Hook context, preventing potential React render loops depending on how the modal was summoned.
*   **Logical Flow**: Massive multi-step execution block:
    1. Grabs the final Display Name they typed.
    2. **Saves the Rule**: Tells the database to permanently link `TXN*AMZN` to `Amazon`.
    3. **Retroactive Update**: `transactionId === -1` is a special flag meaning "We found multiple old transactions with this weird name." It triggers a batch SQL `UPDATE` to fix all past history retroactively. Otherwise, it just fixes the single targeted receipt.
    4. **Emit Event**: It yells `'TRANSACTION_UPDATED'` onto the system radio frequency so any open screens instantly drop their caches and re-query SQLite.

## 3. UI Display Block (Lines 105-134)
```tsx
                    <View style={styles.header}>
                        <Icon name="storefront" size={32} color={colors.primary} />
                        <Text style={styles.title}>New Merchant Detected</Text>
                        <Text style={styles.subtitle}>Save a name for "{merchant.rawName}" ... </Text>
                    </View>

                    <View style={styles.transactionPreview}>
                        <Text style={styles.amount}>{formatCurrency(merchant.amount)}</Text>
                        <Text style={styles.rawName}>From: {merchant.rawName}</Text>
                    </View>
```
*   **Logical Flow**: Renders a warning card. It explicitly prints the exact `merchant.rawName` (the ugly SMS text) so the user understands *why* they are being asked to clarify this.

## 4. Category Dropdown (Lines 136-177)
```tsx
                        <TouchableOpacity style={styles.categorySelector} onPress={() => setShowCategories(!showCategories)}>
                            {selectedCategoryData ? (
                                <View style={styles.selectedCategory}>
                                    <View style={[styles.categoryDot, { backgroundColor: selectedCategoryData.color }]} />
                                    <Text style={styles.categoryText}>{selectedCategoryData.name}</Text>
                                </View>
                            ) : (
                                <Text style={styles.placeholderText}>Select category</Text>
                            )}
                            <Icon name={showCategories ? 'expand-less' : 'expand-more'} ... />
                        </TouchableOpacity>
```
*   **Syntax**: Conditional rendering `? :`
*   **Logical Flow**: Exact same custom dropdown mechanic used in the [TransactionDetailScreen](file:///c:/Users/HP/Downloads/expensetracker/mobile/src/screens/TransactionDetailScreen.tsx#28-260). If an item is selected, draw its color dot and name. If not, draw the placeholder text. Tapping opens a nested `ScrollView` of options.

## 5. Skip Logic (Lines 187-196)
```tsx
                    <View style={styles.actions}>
                        <TouchableOpacity style={styles.skipButton} onPress={handleSkip}>
                            <Text style={styles.skipButtonText}>Skip</Text>
                        </TouchableOpacity>
                        <TouchableOpacity style={styles.saveButton} onPress={handleSave}>
                            <Text style={styles.saveButtonText}>Save</Text>
                        </TouchableOpacity>
                    </View>
```
*   **Logical Flow**: If the user doesn't care to name this unknown merchant, they hit "Skip". It hides the modal and leaves the transaction looking ugly (raw SMS name) in the database.
